content:
agreed, one big question is how to remove incentive structures such as students getting a certain number of publications to graduate, or profs getting publications for funding

these often add pressure, resulting in low quality publications that are safe instead of having long term impact

@ylecun thoughts?

@YangYue_THU Amazing news! 👌

This should be celebrated and become the norm. Many people have already kept explaining  for years why nothing should be blind or anonymous in the peer-review process.

The amount of junk science papers at ML conference must be more than 95% at this point.

@chrsmrrs @iclr_conf Bad decision that hurts students that worked hard on their rebuttals. ACs don’t have the capacity to redo the whole discussion process. 
@iclr_conf
 should revert it.

@BlancheMinerva I don't necessarily disagree, but

"is collusion that rampant?"

yes

@maxim_panov @qberthet @BlackHC @iclr_conf Not a long consequence, but I'll bite. 
You mean all in good faith. How many reviews are assumed to be compromised? How many are not and affected? 
Could you do something less disruptive? (E. G. Warn all ACs on every paper with big changes)

@solarmagic77 https://t.co/lKlYqRhR0Y
0. Openreview 문제로 리뷰어가 공개되었습니다. single-blind가 되었습니다.
1. 이걸로 리뷰어에게... 직접 메일을 보내는 케이스가 있다고는 하더라고요.

@DamienTeney @iclr_conf Agree, and this is a deeper problem concerning the whole community. 
Anyway, can you make the desk reject void now @iclr_conf ?
https://t.co/XwvckmY4ow

@iclr_conf Sure there might not be a good solution here, but reverting all rebuttals and discussions is surely a bad one.

We should presume authors and reviewers are innocent instead of assuming everyone guilty.

Also, the "collusion gang" has many, many more different ways to collude.

@yoavgo OMG Did you all get that? 
Are they mad? 
Like I didn't do anything until now, reading rebuttals pushing people to respond and discuss etc. we had people raising scores and agreeing with review and they cancel everything because they just assume all the conference are liers?! https://t.co/oiyLxb9roT

@prajdabre 1. Will lead to decrease of review quality most likely (too many positive reviews...)

3. What is an issue with that? Why decent paper should not be accepted?

6. Benefit is not clear...

@dhruv2038 People are iffy but I am all for it. My friend @Anonymanasensei
 is helping enable this via 
@VeritusAi

@BestSonnyPanH @MattNiessner You are talking about conferences that are accepting at least 95% junk science papers.

It doesn’t make much of a difference anyway.

They are heavily sponsored to pump the LLM hype.

@iclr_conf @DennisSoemers I tried to write a DM but somehow I can't - what email should I use? 

Is this the right one: andrea.brown@aicons.org ? 

Thanks! https://t.co/CZsz8yKuIe

@PMinervini Theoretically, it makes sense, but it's a total mess.

A lot of overhead for everyone and it breaks rebuttal: the vast majority of them were totally regular...

Luckily I didn't submit this round 😁
